#Text=Rare Middle East cyclone batters Oman
#Text=Thursday , June 7 , 2007
#Text=Tropical Storm Gonu

#Text=headed toward Iran today , after lashing Oman for two days with high winds and torrential rains , and causing at least 23 deaths and the evacuation of more than 20,000 people to emergency shelters .
#Text=Concern was high for the oil industry , as rough seas kept tankers from leaving their ports .
#Text=Such storms are rare in the Middle East .
#Text=Early today , Gonu was weakening and was downgraded to a tropical storm .
#Text=The Joint Typhoon Warning Center projected the storm to continue weakening as it made landfall on Iran 's southeastern coast .
#Text=Offshore Iranian oil installations were expected to be spared , officials said .
#Text=Oman lashed
#Text=In the Omani capital , Muscat yesterday , there were torrential rains and howling winds , a rarity in the quiet coastal city .
#Text=Streets were flooded and emergency vehicles were useless .
#Text=Flights were canceled at Oman 's Seeb International Airport .
#Text=Twenty-three deaths were reported by Omani authorities today .
#Text=Electricity and phone lines were out and roads flooded .
#Text=Police said a body washed ashore in Sur .
#Text=There were also reports of people trapped in homes in low-lying areas of the capital .
#Text=Authorities used mobile-phone text messages to warn people away from dangerous areas .
#Text=Residents were warned to stay at home , or seek shelter in buildings that could withstand the harsh weather .
#Text=Shareefa bint Khalfan , Omani minister of social development , said more than 20,000 people were evacuated to government shelters .
#Text=At Oman 's weather center , where records have been kept since 1890 , metorologists said Gonu was likely the strongest storm to hit Oman since 1977 .
#Text=Milder tropical storms are common mid-May to late June .
#Text=Iran prepares
#Text=In Iran , hundreds of residents of Chabahr , a port on the Gulf of Oman , were evacuated .

#Text=" University and school students were moved to higher ground in the area to avoid the cyclone effects , " Hojjat Ali Shayanfar , head of emergency services in Sistan Baluchistan province , was quoted as saying by the Associated Press .
#Text=Some major roads were flooded in southeastern Iran .
#Text=In the port city of Bandar Abbas , winds shattered windows and knocked down billboards & trees .
#Text=Impact on oil industry
#Text=Oman has relatively small oil fields , and there was little damage to them .
#Text=But oil exports were cut off , as the raging seas kept tankers battened down in port for a third day today .
#Text=To the north , at the world 's third-largest shipping fuel center in Fujairah , United Arab Emirates , all refueling and supply operations were suspended , and ships were kept in their berths .
#Text=At the entrance to the Persian Gulf , the Strait of Hormuz , ships passed through , despite four- to six-foot swells and strong winds .
#Text=About one-fifth of the world 's oil passes through this narrow chokepoint .
#Text=Iran , OPEC 's No. 2 oil exporter , said the storm would not disrupt supplies because its main terminals were inside the Gulf waterway .
#Text=Analysts were mixed on how the storm will affect prices at the gas pump .
#Text=" About 17-21 million barrels a day of oil are coming out of the Persian Gulf .
